Hooking into the Future: A Uniswap Valuation

Kinji Steimetz

Feb 15, 2024 ⋅  17 min read

Key Insights

  • We project hooks to account for 60% of Uniswap's 2028 FDV in our base case. However, it's important to note that a substantial portion of this anticipated growth seems to be already factored into the current token valuation, potentially limiting upside.
  • V4 transforms Uniswap from a spot trading application into a liquidity platform, opening the door to a potential new revenue model by taxing hooks applications instead of traditional swaps.
  • Hooks introduce the capability for Uniswap to venture into new markets, particularly capturing volumes of tokenized assets and perpetual swaps for a broader range of assets.
  • Uniswap V4 cements its status as the premier EVM DEX, poised to expand its market share in EVM DEX volumes significantly.

Revisiting Uniswap V4

In June 2023, Uniswap unveiled its vision for Uniswap V4, marked by adding hooks and implementing singleton. Here's a concise overview of the changes, with a more detailed analysis available in our initial reaction piece.

Hooks

In Uniswap V4, the lifecycle of each liquidity pool is made more flexible through hooks. Unlike the strict sequence of events in V3, hooks allow pool deployers to incorporate custom code at specific points in the pool's lifecycle, such as before or after a swap or LP position change. These hooks serve as plugins, enabling developers to customize interactions between pools, swaps, fees, and LP positions. This promotes the creation of tailored AMM pools by integrating with the smart contracts of Uniswap V4 while maintaining the baseline features introduced in V3.

Singleton and gas efficiency

Uniswap V4 introduces a singleton architecture, consolidating all pools into one contract to reduce gas costs associated with pool creation and eliminating the need to transfer tokens between different contracts during swaps. The singleton structure is coupled with a "flash accounting" system that optimizes asset transfers by only adjusting net balances providing additional gas savings in V4. Additionally, V4 reinstates support for native ETH, further contributing to gas savings.

Implications Uniswap Hooks for the UNI token

Having had time to digest the overarching V4 architecture, we have identified three major implications derived from new V4 features which are:

  • Alternative monetization opportunities for the UNI token.
  • Solidifying Uniswap share on the EVM.
  • Uniswap's expansion into new markets.

Alternative monetization

The introduction of hooks redefines Uniswap from an application to a liquidity platform as hooks effectively are mini-apps built on top of Uniswap’s liquidity layer. This shift is underscored by a fundamental change in its potential revenue model, transitioning from selling the core asset (liquidity) to selling access to it. In contrast to the previously conceived model reliant solely on swap fees charged to Liquidity Providers (LPs), the advent of Hooks empowers Uniswap to levy charges on the additional features integrated atop its pools. This strategic refinement aims to sidestep taxing the providers of Uniswap's most invaluable asset—liquidity—acknowledging liquidity as the core competitive dimension for Decentralized Exchanges (DEXs).

Consequently, we anticipate the protocol entertaining the concept of imposing fees on swaps or withdrawals routed through hooks before implementing a fee switch on traditional pools. This approach aims to capture the enhanced value generated through hook deployments. Essentially, swappers or LPs seeking to leverage the supplementary features facilitated by various hooks would be required to pay for the added functionalities, reflecting a new approach to monetizing the protocol.

Strengthening of Uniswaps hold over EVM DEX share

With the launch of UNI V4, we foresee Uniswap expanding its DEX share on EVM chains as V4 introduces several disincentives for creating a competing DEX outside the Uniswap ecosystem.

Greater expressivity for AMM developers

The primary motivation for developing a new AMM model was to express specific pool or swap preferences impossible within Uniswap V3 architecture. For example, developers may have wanted to implement dynamic fee models or enable a range of onchain order types, which were not possible on V3 and would require the development of a brand new DEX. However, developers can now enhance expressivity by creating hooks, reducing the need to build a new DEX and inheriting the associated customer and liquidity acquisition challenges.

Gas savings

Singleton and flash accounting facilitates the internalization of multi-pool swaps within a single contract, reducing gas costs for users routing transactions through multiple pools. This introduces a Uniswap network effect, as the increased number of tokens held within the protocol creates more opportunities for users to realize savings on efficient multi-pool swaps. In a business where basis points matter, gas efficiencies over other protocols can go a long way to capturing marketshare.

Brand and Development

Launching on Uniswap V4 provides DEX developers access to the established brand and codebase of Uniswap, a trusted name in the crypto space. Building on the Uniswap codebase and utilizing previously deployed hooks minimizes development overhead and eliminates security risks associated with consistently deploying new smart contracts. Instead, developers streamline the development process by focusing on writing and auditing new hooks.

V4 marks an opportunity for Uniswap to expand its share on EVM chains by disincentivizing the rise of new DEX competition and diverting volume from DEXs that have yet to attain critical mass. In our base case model, we assume Uniswap will surpass any DEX that has not achieved a critical mass, defined as a minimum of 3% volume share, on chains where Uniswap is operational. This assumption implies an increase in Uniswap's overall volume share on deployed chains, from 60% to slightly over 70%.

Expansion to New Markets

The introduction of hooks transforms Uniswap from a DEX application to a liquidity platform, where developers can attract and utilize liquidity for applications beyond basic swaps. Hooks open the door for wide experimentation with three core areas poised to see the most benefit:

  • Tokenized assets or Real World Assets
  • Derivatives (specifically long-tail assets)
  • Hook-Apps (mini apps such as a DCA tool)

Tokenization

Introduction to Tokenization on Uniswap

Despite the potential for tokenizing physical or intangible assets, the regulatory requirements for KYC and AML pose obstacles to onchain tokenization. As a result, many tokenization platforms operate within relatively isolated systems, where only whitelisted addresses can swap tokenized assets in a permissioned market. However, KYC hooks in Uniswap V4 allow tokenization protocols to leverage Uniswap liquidity pools while maintaining KYC compliance.

Instead of functioning independently of the Uniswap system, a liquidity pool holding tokenized assets can use hooks to ensure that swappers and Liquidity Providers (LPs) have the necessary permissions such as a valid KYC NFT to interact with the tokenized asset pool. This approach enhances composability for tokenized assets by eliminating the requirement for users to engage with separate protocols to execute a multi-token swap, streamlining the process within a single transaction. Additionally, it enhances capital efficiency as users are not required to utilize a permissioned chain and can leverage existing Uniswap liquidity for multi-hop swaps.

Total Addressable Market

We have utilized two reference points to project the TAM for tokenized asset swaps. Initially, we consider the CEO of Onyx by JP Morgan's statement targeting the transfer of $5 billion to $10 billion USD over their blockchain platform within two years, annualizing to $1.25 trillion to $2.5 trillion in tokenized volume. Using this as a foundation for estimating the TAM of tokenized asset trading, our 2026 base case is set at $1.5 trillion in tokenization volume.

We anticipate growth in tokenization volume will align with the overall market growth for tokenized assets. We model this by referencing the 2023 growth in non-stablecoin tokenized assets, which was 65% according to 21Shares. However, we expect growth to accelerate in the coming years due to increased activity in tokenization projects such as Ondo, Superstate, and MakerRWA. Consequently, we have adjusted our CAGR from 2026 to 2028 to 70% in our base case, resulting in an expected total volume of tokenized assets surpassing $4.3 trillion by 2028.

Recognizing that tokenizing assets doesn't guarantee onchain trading, we assumed that the ratio of onchain trading to offchain trading would be similar to DEX-to-CEX volume ratios. In our base case, we model Uniswap accounting for 15% of tokenization volumes, assuming that onchain volumes will gain share, leveling just above the peak DEX market share of 12.76% in May 2023. This adjustment results in a base case volume for Uniswap reaching $650 billion.

However, with programmable access rules onchain, there is substantial potential for a greater volume of tokenized assets to be processed onchain rather than through centralized exchanges (CEXs). JPMorgan, as an illustration, can establish and enforce its own access rules onchain, freeing itself from reliance on a CEX for rule implementation. Therefore, assuming the current decentralized exchange (DEX) to centralized exchange (CEX) volume ratios for spot token markets is a conservative estimate.

Potential Monetization

Leveraging Uniswap for tokenized assets establishes a business vertical akin to a specialized Decentralized Exchange (DEX). Consequently, we assess the value of the tokenized assets vertical using a revenue multiple comparable to other DEXs. To project revenue, we apply a range of take rates on the volume, representing fees the protocol could charge hooks providers based on potential fee switches governed by UNI governance.

We assume that both swappers and liquidity providers will exhibit price sensitivity. Therefore, we anticipate minimal efforts at monetization to maintain affordability for both parties, using a conservative protocol take-rate of 11% on the average Liquidity Provider (LP) revenue of 0.13% in our forecasts. As a result, our 2028 base case forecast indicates that tokenization hooks could generate just under $93 million.

Perpetual Swaps

Introduction to Perpetuals on Uniswap

Hooks enable the in-house development of protocols tapping into Uniswap liquidity for perpetual markets, reducing reliance on external applications. These hooks can adopt approaches similar to InfinityPools or Gammaswap to secure spot liquidity for perpetuals. Traders borrow concentrated LP positions', ensuring they can sell the leveraged asset for the borrowed cash amount. Closing a trade involves using external decentralized exchanges through flash transactions, where both the swap and the re-deposit back to InfinityPools happen at the same time. This flexibility enables traders to take profits anytime during the loan, but it comes with the caveat of potential slippage and swap fees when using external DEX.

While perpetual swap markets are well-established, the landscape features intense competition between various onchain and centralized services. However, perpetual markets built on top of Uniswap can uniquely target the long tail of crypto assets such as recently deployed memecoins or protocol tokens. As long as liquidity exists on Uniswap, LP positions can be used in a leverage model. Therefore, we envision Perpetual Hooks primarily targeting the memecoin market, leveraging the flexibility offered by Uniswap's diverse asset pool to be first to market for new memecoins.

Total Addressable Market

To assess the potential market opportunity for memecoin perpetuals built on hooks, we combined our projected growth in the spot market with memecoins' historical share of spot volumes and a historical perpetual-to-spot volume ratio. Memecoin volume share peaked at 18% in May 2021 but has since declined to 4.27% in January 2024. We cautiously anticipate challenges for memecoins in growing their volume share, believing there will be an increased focus on more practical applications of crypto and associated assets.

In our base case, we model memecoin volume share to remain flat at 4.5%, with an optimistic bull case expanding share to 8% (aligned with 2023 averages) and a bear case foreseeing memecoins fading to only 1% of total spot volume.

We apply  DOGE's 2023 average perpetual-to-spot volume ratio of 1.67 for our memecoin spot forecasts to estimate memecoin perpetuals volume. The outcome is a projected TAM of $1.1 trillion in memecoin-related perpetuals by 2028. Within this market, we forecast Uniswap to capture 60% of this specific volume, positioned between our bullish case of 80% (correlating with Uniswap's share of DEX volumes) and our bear case of 40% (reflecting larger decentralized perpetual protocols share of onchain perpetuals).

Potential monetization

We assess Uniswap perpetuals as a revenue-generating segment, tying its valuation to the FDV-to-protocol revenue multiple of comparable peers. Our revenue projections hinge on applying profit margins similar to GMX, an onchain AMM perpetual protocol, at 0.18% of the volume. While this serves as our base case, it's important to note that Uniswap might command higher trading costs to compensate Liquidity Providers (LPs) for increased risk, especially with memecoins.

In our base case, we remove fees paid to LPs from revenue, implementing an 11% take-rate for protocol fees, resulting in a final base case take-rate of 0.019% on perpetual volume. As a result, our base case anticipates Uniswap generating approximately $132 million in protocol revenue from perpetuals by the year 2028.

Hook-Apps

Currently, Uniswap only facilitates market orders through its liquidity pools, leading to the development of external applications, such as DEX aggregators or Telegram Bots, to accommodate more advanced order types (limit orders and automated take-profit or stop-loss orders). However, hooks empower developers to integrate order expressivity directly into pools, reducing reliance on external applications.

In our modeling approach, we anticipate a shift in trading behavior on Uniswap, with a portion of the volume migrating from standard market orders to more expressive orders facilitated by Hooks, termed Hook-apps. For our base case, we used the share of limit orders on 1inch, ~25%, as an indicator for the demand for expressive orders, forming our base case assumption that 25% of Uniswap orders will be routed through various Hook-apps.

In terms of monetization, we apply the same take-rate assumptions employed in the tokenization context, leading to a potential revenue estimate of $49 million in our 2028 base case.

Sum of Parts Valuation Approach

Given Uniswap's potential expansion into new markets, we opted for a sum-of-the-parts valuation approach where each business line (DEX, Tokenization, Perpetuals, and Hook-apps) is valued separately and combined for a final fully diluted valuation (FDV) based on the assumptions we outlined above.

DEX Valuation

We employed a top-down methodology to assess the valuation of Uniswap's traditional DEX volumes, defined as swaps that do not use hooks. Our approach commenced by forecasting the total spot volumes in the broader cryptocurrency market derived from historical growth rates of spot volume. We based our bull case on a historical CAGR of 30% spanning from May 2020 (the initiation of the last halving cycle) to the conclusion of 2023.

However, recognizing the dissimilarity in market conditions, particularly the absence of widespread monetary stimulus compared to the previous bull market cycle, we adjusted our base case CAGR to 20%, representing 75% of the historical growth numbers. This results in forecasting approximately $15.2T in total crypto spot volume by 2028.

We assess Uniswap's share of total spot volumes by incorporating DEX's market share of spot volumes, EVM's share of DEX volumes, and Uniswap's share of EVM volumes into our model.

Uniswap Share = DEX share of spot × EVM share of DEX × UNI share of EVM

In our base case, we assume a DEX share of spot volumes at 15%, using the same logic applied in projecting Uniswap's share of tokenization volumes. Additionally, we forecast EVM share to remain steady at 80%, reflecting its closing position in 2023. Furthermore, we anticipate Uniswap's EVM share to grow to 73%, achieved by surpassing any EVM DEX with less than 3% volume share, driven by disincentives for creating new DEXs following the launch of V3.

To determine a valuation for traditional DEX volumes, we employ an FDV-to-volume multiple, yielding our final DEX valuation. Uniswap's FDV-to-volume multiple has compressed to 0.14 and we anticipate this number to further compress to 0.005.

Our rationale is based on combining the FDV-to-revenue of peers to infer Uniswap's implied revenue and subsequently applying historical volumes to ascertain an implied take-rate on volume. Current valuations imply a take-rate on volume of 0.04%, suggesting the protocol captures nearly 30% of total fees. However, we argue for a more realistic protocol take rate and a 0.005 FDV-to-volume multiple implies a take-rate on the total volume of 0.013%, indicating the protocol captures 10% of total fees.  Applying our FDV-to-volume multiple to our volume forecasts outputs a 2028 FDV of $5.1B, which we add to the FDV of the different hook segments for a final valuation.

Hooks Valuation

Having applied revenue assumptions to each of Uniswap's potential hook verticals, we can determine segment valuations by applying revenue multiples. Both Tokenization and Hook-app verticals exhibit characteristics of specialized DEX platforms. To establish an FDV-to-revenue multiple, we utilized a peer group of DEXs, resulting in an average multiple of 38.0. This multiple was then applied to revenue forecasts for these segments to estimate potential valuations.

For the perpetual vertical, we employed an FDV-to-revenue multiple from a peer group specifically composed of AMM-style perpetual protocols. We focused on AMM perps in our peer group due to the belief that Uniswap's perpetual hooks model closely resembles these protocols, emphasizing passive liquidity over an order book design. The resulting multiple was 21.8, applied to revenue forecasts for estimating the potential FDV of the perpetual vertical.

Valuation Insights and Risks

Our valuation model suggests that hooks will constitute over half of Uniswap's future valuation. However, we caution that much of this potential upside seems to be already factored into Uniswap's FDV, given the market's overestimation of implied take rates. We perceive a 100% 5-year upside as lacking an enticing risk-reward profile, particularly considering the substantial downside risks:

Assumption of Stable EVM DEX Volumes

One of the key risks in our model is the assumption of the EVM maintaining dominance, despite the recent surge in non-EVM chains, particularly Solana. The sustainability of EVM dominance is not guaranteed, and a shift to low-cost alternatives with real use cases could undermine Uniswap's position as the premier DEX as volumes migrate to ecosystems where Uniswap lacks a presence.

Assumption of Hook Adoption

While we identify clear use cases for hooks, their success is contingent on user and developer acceptance. Users might also migrate away from hooks due to additional security concerns, where users must not only trust Uniswap but also each hook the user is interacting with.

Potential Degradation of Smart Routing

Hooks could negatively impact the user experience by introducing significant overhead for routers searching for the best prices. As new pools and hooks emerge, routers must constantly evaluate, integrate, and simulate hook transactions, potentially hampering the ability to ensure optimal execution for swappers. If routers struggle to keep up with the growing complexity of pools and hooks, users might lose confidence in execution quality, leading them to explore alternative platforms.

Assumption of Spot Markets and DEX Share Growth

Our model relies on the assumption of continued growth in both crypto spot markets and the overall DEX share of spot volumes. While we are confident in the ongoing expansion of both segments, we acknowledge the inherent two-way risk associated with these forecasts.

Closing Summary

The introduction of Uniswap V4 can stimulate volume growth for the protocol by increasing market share on EVM chains and venturing into new markets with the development of hooks. This upgrade also opens avenues for Uniswap to generate revenue by imposing charges on the added functionalities enabled by hooks. Although these advancements present positive prospects for the protocol, it's worth noting that a significant portion of this upside appears to be reflected in the token's valuation. Considering the downside risks in our model, we approach the potential risk-reward profile with skepticism.
